Hi,

I'm using [ui-sortable](https://github.com/angular-ui/ui-sortable) to add drag and drop to my tables. I'm aware of other libraries to do the same but this suited our needs best.

The problem of combining this with Smart Table is that when dragging to re-order the table, the effect is that the change to the `rowCollection` (using the same naming in the [docs](http://lorenzofox3.github.io/smart-table-website/) stSafeSrc example) does not change the length of the collection, nor does it change the reference to the collection, so the two watches on `stSafeSrc` (one for length, one on the reference to the object) do not trigger the listeners. Because the listeners do not get triggered, this puts the `rowCollection` and the `displayedCollection` out of sync.

One way of combining the two successfully is make the `$watch` on `stSafeSrc` use `objectEquality == true`, the third parameter to `$scope.$watch`:
```
    if ($attrs.stSafeSrc) {
      ...
      $scope.$watch(function () {
        return safeGetter($scope);
      }, function (newValue, oldValue) {
        if (newValue !== oldValue) {
          updateSafeCopy();
        }
      }, true); 
    }
```

I tried this and it fixed the problem.

Unfortunately, this *might* have performance implications:
> When objectEquality == true, inequality of the watchExpression is determined according to the angular.equals function. To save the value of the object for later comparison, the angular.copy function is used. This therefore means that watching complex objects will have adverse memory and performance implications.

See [$rootScope.Scope](https://docs.angularjs.org/api/ng/type/$rootScope.Scope)

I'm wondering if the performance implications of changing the `$watch` on `stSafeSrc` in this way have been measured or considered?

If it does indeed hurt performance for large tables - which certainly seems likely - would the ability to optionally set watching with `objectEquality == true` ever fit in as a possible addition to the API?

Alternatively, is there a better way of dealing with this issue?

I can provide a plunkr if the issue is unclear from my description. Thanks for your time and for this useful module.

Hello everyone, especially @miguelgrinberg !

Is there a way to control SocketIO app via web api. To be more precise i want use web api (Flask) to control SocketIO handlers. For example, i want have WebApi method, that can setup new message handler for SocketIO app.

This is sketch of this service, but this obviously doesn't work as i expected.

```
import socketio
import eventlet.wsgi
from flask import Flask, jsonify, abort, make_response, request

app = Flask(__name__)
sio = socketio.Server()

@app.route('/')
def index():
    return 'Hello folks! This is mock SocketIO server for testing.'

@app.route('/set_sio_handler', methods=['POST'])
def set_sio_handler():
    @sio.on('commands')
    def message_handler(sid, msg):
        if msg['data']['command'] == request.json['command']:
            response_msg = {'handler': msg['handler'],
                            'data': {'result':   request.json['result']}}
            sio.emit('commands', response_msg)

if __name__ == '__main__':
    mid = socketio.Middleware(sio, app)
    eventlet.wsgi.server(eventlet.listen(('127.0.0.1', 1234)), mid)
```

Are there any suggestions how to do this?

